This SPICE simulation shows the actual voltage across R$_{2}$ of the test circuit, the null detector's voltage, and the voltage across the adjustable voltage source, as that source is adjusted from 0 volts to 6 volts in 0.5 volt steps.  In the output of this simulation, you will notice that the voltage across R$_{2}$ \textit{is} impacted significantly when the measurement circuit is unbalanced, returning to its true voltage only when there is practically zero voltage across the null detector.  At that point, of course, the adjustable voltage source is at a value of 3.000 volts: precisely equal to the (unaffected) test circuit voltage drop.
 

 

What is the lesson to be learned from this simulation?  That a potentiometric voltmeter avoids impacting the test circuit \textit{only} when it is in a condition of perfect balance ("null") with the test circuit!
 


