\section{ Introduction}
\index{Alternating current}
\index{AC}
 

"AC" stands for \textbf{A}lternating \textbf{C}urrent, which can refer to either voltage or current that alternates in polarity or direction, respectively.  These experiments are designed to introduce you to several important concepts specific to AC.
 

\index{Power supply}
\index{Transformer}
 

A convenient source of AC voltage is household wall-socket power, which presents significant shock hazard.  In order to minimize this hazard while taking advantage of the convenience of this source of AC, a small \textit{power supply} will be the first project, consisting of a \textit{transformer} that steps the hazardous voltage (110 to 120 volts AC, RMS) down to 12 volts or less.  The title of "power supply" is somewhat misleading.  This device does not really act as a source or \textit{supply} of power, but rather as a power \textit{converter}, to reduce the hazardous voltage of wall-socket power to a much safer level.
 


\vfil \eject 

\section{ Transformer -- power supply}
\index{Experiment: AC power supply}
 

\textbf{PARTS AND MATERIALS}
 

\begin{itemize}
\item Power transformer, 120VAC step-down to 12VAC, with center-tapped secondary winding (Radio Shack catalog \# 273-1365, 273-1352, or 273-1511).
\item Terminal strip with at least three terminals.
\item Household wall-socket power plug and cord.
\item Line cord switch.
\item Box (optional).
\item Fuse and fuse holder (optional).
\end{itemize}
 

Power transformers may be obtained from old radios, which can usually be obtained from a thrift store for a few dollars (or less!).  The radio would also provide the power cord and plug necessary for this project.  Line cord switches may be obtained from a hardware store.  If you want to be absolutely sure what kind of transformer you're getting, though, you should purchase one from an electronics supply store.
 

\index{Fuse, slow-blow}
 

If you decide to equip your power supply with a fuse, be sure to get a \textit{slow-acting}, or \textit{slow-blow} fuse.  Transformers may draw high "surge" currents when initially connected to an AC source, and these transient currents will blow a fast-acting fuse.  Determine the proper current rating of the fuse by dividing the transformer's "VA" rating by 120 volts: in other words, calculate the full allowable primary winding current and size the fuse accordingly.
 

\bigskip 
 

\textbf{CROSS-REFERENCES}
 

 

\textit{Lessons In Electric Circuits}, Volume 2, chapter 1: "Basic AC Theory"
 

 

\textit{Lessons In Electric Circuits}, Volume 2, chapter 9: "Transformers"
 

\bigskip 
 

\textbf{LEARNING OBJECTIVES}
 

\begin{itemize}
\item Transformer voltage step-down behavior.
\item Purpose of tapped windings.
\item Safe wiring techniques for power cords.
\end{itemize}
